{
  "_dft": {
    "_doc": "Memory BIST — March C− algorithm on a 16×8 RAM, with TEST_MODE mux collar.\n\n  SHIPS WITH A PRE-INJECTED FAULT: cell 5 is stuck-at-1 (whole-word).\n  The MBIST will detect it and end in FAIL with failAddr=5. To see\n  the clean PASS path, click cell [addr=5, WORD] in the DFT panel's\n  CELL FAULTS grid until it returns to clean (·), RESET, then START.\n\n  WHAT'S IN THE SCENE:\n    • RAM   — 4 addr-bit × 8 data-bit (16 cells of 8 bits each).\n              Pre-loaded fault: cellFaults[5] = stuck-at-1 (whole word).\n    • MBIST — Memory BIST controller running March C−:\n              { ⇕w0; ⇑r0,w1; ⇑r1,w0; ⇓r0,w1; ⇓r1,w0; ⇕r0 }\n    • 4 BUS_MUXes — the 'MBIST collar': ADDR / DATA / WE / RE are\n        switched between FUNCTIONAL drivers (the 4 INPUT pads on the\n        far left, unused in this demo) and the MBIST controller, by\n        the TEST_MODE output of the MBIST. When TEST_MODE=1 the MBIST\n        drives the RAM; when TEST_MODE=0 the functional drivers do.\n    • START / RESET — pulse START on tick 1 (via stepValues) to arm.\n    • Observable outputs: DONE, PASS, FAIL, TEST_MODE, STATE (3-bit),\n        CUR_ADDR (4-bit), Q (RAM read-back, 8-bit).\n\n  HOW TO RUN (interview script):\n    1. Open the DFT panel (T). Scroll to MEMORY BIST. Note the orange\n       'WORD' chip on row addr=5 in the CELL FAULTS grid — that's the\n       injected stuck-at-1 fault.\n    2. Press RUN, then STEP / AUTO CLK. Watch the live grid:\n       state walks IDLE → SETUP → W0_UP → RW1_UP, addr counts up.\n    3. Around tick ~36, the MBIST reaches addr=5 in RW1_UP and reads\n       0xFF where it expected 0x00. The FSM flips to FAIL, the panel\n       shows failAddr=5, and the lamps assert FAIL=1.\n\n  TO SEE THE CLEAN PASS PATH:\n    1. Click the orange chip at [addr=5, WORD] three times to cycle\n       it back to clean (· in the chip — the fault is removed).\n    2. RESET (pulse the RESET input), then START again.\n    3. The MBIST now runs end-to-end and ends DONE / PASS (~243 ticks).\n\n  PER-BIT FAULTS:\n    Click an individual bit column (B0..B7) on any address to inject\n    a single-bit s-a fault. The panel's failBit field will pin the\n    exact bit that the March test caught.\n\n  WHY THE TEST_MODE COLLAR MATTERS:\n    In a real SoC, the RAM is also driven by functional logic (a CPU,\n    a DMA, a vision pipeline, etc.). The MUXes let the test mode\n    take over the RAM without disturbing the functional wiring,\n    and release it back to functional mode after DONE/FAIL."
  },
